through a series of questions. Many of the questions address practical matters: Do you really need to stretch? Which running shoes best suit your form and foot strike? Does carbo-loading lore stand up to scientific scrutiny—could a big bowl of spaghetti be the difference between a PR and a DNF? Other questions enhance appreciation for the incredible feats of the sport’s great athletes. (What would it take to run a two-hour marathon? Perfect weather, a straight, flat course, competition, and a lot of luck!) The answer to each question is presented in a straightforward, accessible manner, with accompanying infographics. Whether you’re a beginner or a seasoned runner with many miles and medals behind you, Running Science is a must-have for anyone interested in the fascinating science behind the sport.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aRunningxPhysiological aspects. 0aRunningxPhysiology. 0aRunningxphysiology. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh1 aBarnsley, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrewer, Jown, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharalambous, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraighead, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkins, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPedlar, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https:/